			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">How about 5 factions like this:
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Imperial Remnant</span>
<br />
These guys are the survivors of the Empire in AS 1.0
<br />
Archrival: New Republic
<br />
Enemy: Rebel Coalition
<br />
Friend: Magellanic Refugees
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">New Republic</span>
<br />
These guys are the ones who overthrew the Empire in AS 1.0
<br />
Archrival: Imperial Remnant
<br />
Enemy: Magellanic Refugees
<br />
Friend: Rebel Coalition
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Rebel Coalition</span>
<br />
These guys helped the Republicans defeat the Empire only because they detest the Magellanics.
<br />
Archrival: Magellanic Refugees
<br />
Enemy: Imperial Remnant
<br />
Friend: New Republic
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Magellanic Refugees</span>
<br />
The Magellanic Races
<br />
Archrival: Rebel Coalition
<br />
Enemy: New Republic
<br />
Friend: Imperial Remnant
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Neutral Powers</span>
<br />
Isolationists
<br />

<br />
Everyone would start off in the Neutral Powers faction, then, they can join one of their choice when their newbie turns end.  After that, their relations with the various factions vary depending on what actions they take, for instance, attacking a player will boost your relations with the archrival faction of that player and drop your relations with the player's own faction.
<br />

<br />
If your relations with another faction get high enough, you can switch faction.  It is relatively easy to switch to a friend faction, difficult to switch to an enemy faction, and impossible to switch to an archrival faction.
<br />

<br />
Each faction might confer different strengths and weaknesses and each would have it's own set of ranks.
<br />

<br />
Flame away!</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
